## Finding: Ideal End-State Reverse Analysis — Missing Go/No-Go Gate

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: Working backward from a perfectly completed Phase 1: the team would have a signed Go/No-Go decision document before entering Phase 2. This document would capture: validated problem statement, evidence from user research (N interviews, key finding summaries), competitive positioning (why we win), market size estimate, business model viability check, prioritized feature list (MoSCoW/RICE scored), North Star metric defined, key assumptions listed with test results, and stakeholder sign-offs. NONE of the current 9 Phase 1 skills produce or even reference a Go/No-Go gate. A team can complete all 9 existing skills and still proceed to Phase 2 to build something that is economically unviable, technically infeasible, or already validated as unwanted by users. There is no forcing function that synthesizes all Phase 1 work into a final decision artifact.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill `go_no_go_gate` in Phase 1 (runs last). Trigger: "ready for Phase 2?", "go or no-go decision", "should we build this?". Scope: Aggregates outputs from all Phase 1 skills into a single Decision Brief (1-2 pages), applies a weighted viability scorecard (user evidence, market size, competitive position, technical feasibility, business model, team capability), requires explicit "GO" or "NO-GO" answer with reasoning, and blocks Phase 2 entry until signed.
### Cross-Phase Impact: This is the single most impactful gap. Every downstream phase inherits the consequences of a missing Go/No-Go gate. Projects that should have been killed in Phase 1 consume Phase 2-7 resources.
================================================================

## Finding: Perfect Phase 1 Would Have Produced a PRD — No PRD Skill Exists

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: Reverse engineering from what Phase 2 (feature_architecture, schema_standards) actually needs to start: a Product Requirements Document (PRD) containing the full product vision, user personas, core user journeys, feature list with acceptance criteria, non-functional requirements, out-of-scope list, and success metrics. The current Phase 1 skills produce: discovery notes (client_discovery), a competitive report (competitive_analysis), a spec per feature (idea_to_spec), a priority ranking (prioritization_frameworks), metric definitions (product_metrics), a client proposal (proposal_generator), user research findings (user_research), and user stories (user_story_standards). None of these is a PRD. There is no skill that synthesizes all Phase 1 outputs into a single coherent product requirements document. Phase 2 receives a pile of disparate documents instead of one integrated source of truth.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill `prd_generator` in Phase 1 (runs late in sequence, after research and prioritization). Trigger: "generate PRD", "create product requirements", "write the PRD". Scope: Synthesizes all Phase 1 outputs (user research findings, competitive landscape, prioritized feature list, metric definitions, user stories) into a structured PRD with: Executive Summary, Problem Statement, User Personas, Core User Journeys, Feature List (with ACs), NFRs, Out-of-Scope, Success Metrics, and Risks. PRD becomes the canonical input to Phase 2.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without a PRD, Phase 2 architects must read 5-9 separate documents to understand what to build. Architecture decisions get made with incomplete context. Phase 3 (Build) developers lack a single reference document.
================================================================

## Finding: Perfect Phase 1 Would Have Validated Willingness to Pay — Not Just "Need"

### Gap Type: MISSING_SKILL
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: user_research validates whether users have a problem. client_discovery captures stated budget range. But no skill validates actual willingness to pay (WTP) for the proposed solution. The Mom Test rules in user_research correctly note that "Would you pay for this?" is a bad question. But the skill provides no validated replacement methodology: no letter of intent (LOI) collection, no pre-sale/waitlist mechanism, no Van Westendorp price sensitivity analysis, no conjoint analysis for pricing, and no deposit-taking as validation. Stated budget and actual purchase behavior are completely different signals. A perfect Phase 1 would include at least one piece of evidence that someone has committed real money or a real letter of intent.
### Proposed Resolution: Add "Willingness to Pay Validation" sub-section to user_research skill covering: Van Westendorp price sensitivity model (4-question pricing survey), letter of intent (LOI) collection template, pre-sale / waitlist page setup, and interpretation rules (what constitutes sufficient WTP evidence at different project scales: 1 LOI for high-ticket B2B vs. 50 waitlist sign-ups for consumer SaaS).
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without WTP validation, pricing decisions in proposal_generator are disconnected from market reality. Phase 5 (Ship) pricing is set based on cost-plus reasoning rather than value-based evidence.
================================================================

## Finding: Perfect Phase 1 Would Have Defined User Personas — Not Just Segments

### Gap Type: SHALLOW_COVERAGE
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: user_research covers interview techniques and synthesis into findings. prioritization_frameworks has a "Who uses this?" field. idea_to_spec has a WHO field. But none of these skills produces a formal user persona document — a composite behavioral archetype that captures: demographics, goals, frustrations, technical proficiency, current tools, decision-making triggers, and a behavioral scenario. competitive_analysis mentions "freelancers underserved" but produces no persona. A perfect Phase 1 would produce 2-4 validated personas that all subsequent Phase 2 design decisions reference. Currently, Phase 2 designs for an abstract "user" rather than a named, characterized, validated persona.
### Proposed Resolution: Add "Persona Development" as a Phase 6 (synthesis) step within user_research, or create a dedicated section that converts interview findings into structured persona documents. Template should include: Name/archetype, demographics, primary job-to-be-done, key frustrations, technical comfort level, current workarounds, and a day-in-the-life scenario. Personas should be explicitly referenced by user_story_standards ("As [Persona Name]...") and idea_to_spec WHO field.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 2 design decisions (UX flows, data models, UI complexity) are persona-dependent. Designing without personas produces generic interfaces that serve no one well.
