## Finding: FAILURE MODE — Enterprise Context Breaks client_discovery Completely

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: CRITICAL
### Evidence: client_discovery is designed for a single-contact 15-30 minute call with a small business owner. When the context changes to enterprise: (1) the single contact is rarely the decision-maker; (2) procurement requires multiple stakeholders, legal review, and compliance questionnaires; (3) budget is departmental and requires ROI justification, not a $1,500-5,000 price range check; (4) "how many people on your team?" is an inadequate enterprise sizing question; (5) compliance requirements (SOC2, HIPAA, GDPR, FedRAMP) are not surfaced at all. An enterprise discovery call using this skill would miss: security questionnaire requirements, legal/procurement process, integration requirements (SSO, LDAP, SAML), data processing agreements (DPA), and the fact that the person on the call has zero signing authority. The skill has no branching for enterprise vs. SMB context.
### Proposed Resolution: Add an enterprise discovery variant to client_discovery with: deal size branching (< $10K → SMB flow; > $10K → enterprise flow), stakeholder mapping questions (who are the champion, economic buyer, technical evaluator, legal reviewer?), compliance/security pre-qualification (SOC2 compliance requirement? GDPR DPA needed?), procurement process questions (how long does your PO process take?), and integration requirements discovery (do you need SSO/SAML?).
### Cross-Phase Impact: Enterprise deals that go through SMB discovery produce proposals that die in legal/procurement. The Phase 5 (Ship) enterprise GTM motion fails at the very first touchpoint.
================================================================

## Finding: FAILURE MODE — product_metrics Breaks for Non-Digital / Offline Products

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: product_metrics assumes a digital product with event tracking, DAU/MAU measurement, funnel analytics, and in-app NPS. When the context changes to: physical products, hybrid digital/physical workflows, B2B services (not SaaS), or regulated industries (healthcare, finance) — the AARRR framework and dashboard design guidance breaks down. For SMB service delivery (the primary use case of smb_launchpad), "weekly active users" is not a meaningful metric — project delivery milestones and client satisfaction scores are. For offline onboarding flows, "activation rate" cannot be measured via in-app events. The skill has no variant for non-SaaS business models.
### Proposed Resolution: Add business model variants to product_metrics: (1) SaaS variant (current content), (2) Service delivery variant (project-based metrics: on-time delivery rate, scope change rate, client satisfaction score, referral rate), (3) Marketplace variant (GMV, take rate, buyer/seller retention), (4) Content/Media variant (time on content, completion rate, subscriber growth). Each variant should have its own North Star and AARRR equivalent.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Service delivery projects (smb_launchpad workflow) have no appropriate metrics guidance. Practitioners default to SaaS metrics that don't apply, producing misleading dashboards.
================================================================

## Finding: FAILURE MODE — user_story_standards Breaks for API-Only / Infrastructure Products

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: user_story_standards is designed for user-facing features with "As a [user]..." framing. When the context changes to: internal APIs (the "user" is another service), developer tools (the "user" is a developer building something else), infrastructure components (the "user" is an automated system), or data pipeline features (no human user exists) — the Classic user story format breaks down. The skill notes "As a mobile app, I want to fetch user profiles via API" but provides no guidance for: technical stories, spike stories (research/investigation), infrastructure stories, or API contract definitions. Developer tools built on this framework will have poorly specified technical requirements.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to user_story_standards: (1) Technical story templates for APIs and infrastructure ("System Story: The [API endpoint] must [behavior] so that [consumer service] can [capability]"), (2) Spike story format ("Research Spike: Investigate [unknown] to determine [decision], timebox: [N] hours, output: [decision document]"), (3) Non-functional story templates (performance: "The system must handle [X] requests/second at P95 < [Y]ms"), (4) API contract story format with request/response schema.
### Cross-Phase Impact: API-first or developer-tool products built on this framework will have user stories that don't capture technical requirements. Phase 3 (Build) developers will fill gaps with assumptions.
================================================================

## Finding: FAILURE MODE — competitive_analysis Is Static and Becomes Stale Immediately

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: competitive_analysis produces a point-in-time snapshot of the market. There is no mechanism for keeping it current. Competitors launch new features (daily), adjust pricing (monthly), get acquired, or shut down. The skill's "Competitor Discovery Checklist" is a one-time activity. By the time Phase 3 (Build) finishes — often 3-12 months after Phase 1 — the competitive landscape documented in Phase 1 is obsolete. There is no guidance on: how often to refresh the analysis, what triggers a re-analysis (competitor product launch, funding round, market event), or how to track competitor changes during development.
### Proposed Resolution: Add a "Competitive Monitoring" section to competitive_analysis covering: (1) Automated monitoring setup (Google Alerts for competitor names, G2/Capterra review monitoring, Crunchbase funding alerts), (2) Refresh cadence (full re-analysis quarterly, quick pulse monthly), (3) Trigger-based re-analysis criteria (competitor raises Series A, launches competing feature, changes pricing), (4) Competitive change log format that feeds into Phase 1 → Phase 2 handoff updates.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 5 (Ship) launches into a competitive landscape that was documented 6+ months earlier. GTM positioning is stale. Phase 3 builds features that competitors have since released.
================================================================

## Finding: FAILURE MODE — idea_to_spec Breaks for Regulated Industries

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: idea_to_spec's SECURITY section contains three fields: Auth (Required/Optional/Public), Who (Owner only / Role-based / All users), Validation (what to check). When the context changes to regulated industries — healthcare (HIPAA), finance (PCI-DSS, SOX), legal, or government (FedRAMP) — these three fields are wholly inadequate. HIPAA requires: audit logging (who accessed what data when), minimum necessary access principle, business associate agreements, PHI de-identification, and breach notification procedures. PCI-DSS requires: cardholder data isolation, encryption at rest and in transit, tokenization, and vulnerability scanning. The spec template will be used by practitioners building in these industries with no warning about the regulatory gap.
### Proposed Resolution: Add a "Compliance Tier" field to idea_to_spec OVERVIEW (Standard / GDPR / HIPAA / PCI-DSS / SOX / FedRAMP / Custom). When a non-Standard tier is selected, the SECURITY section expands to include: applicable regulatory requirements, data classification requirements, audit logging requirements, retention and deletion policies, and a pointer to the relevant compliance checklist in Phase 4 (Secure). Optionally, reference a `regulatory_requirements` companion skill.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) will discover regulatory gaps after architecture is built and code is written. Retrofitting HIPAA compliance into a non-compliant architecture is expensive and sometimes impossible without redesign.
================================================================

## Finding: FAILURE MODE — prioritization_frameworks Breaks for Small Teams / Solo Founders

### Gap Type: FAILURE_MODE_UNCOVERED
### Severity: LOW
### Evidence: RICE scoring requires estimating Reach (users per quarter), Impact (per user), and Effort (person-weeks). For a solo founder or 2-person team with zero users, RICE produces nonsensical scores: Reach = 0 (no users yet), Effort = infinitely large relative to capacity. MoSCoW works better at this scale, but the skill's guidance ("Must Haves should be about 60% of your total effort. If everything is a 'Must Have,' you haven't prioritized.") doesn't account for the reality that an MVP often HAS to be 80-100% Must Have features to be minimally viable. The Kano model requires existing user data to validate which features are "Basic" vs. "Excitement." All three frameworks assume more context than early-stage startups have.
### Proposed Resolution: Add a "Stage-Appropriate Framework" selector: (1) Pre-product (0 users): Use "Kill Criteria" framework — for each feature, what's the minimum version that provides value and what happens if we skip it entirely?; (2) Early traction (< 100 users): MoSCoW only, maximum 3 Must Have items; (3) Growth (100+ users): RICE scoring with user data; (4) Mature product: Full RICE + Kano with A/B test data.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Early-stage teams applying enterprise prioritization frameworks produce over-engineered MVPs. Phase 3 (Build) consumes runway on the wrong features.
================================================================

