## Finding: INDUSTRY DEVIATION — No Design Thinking / Double Diamond Process

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: The IDEO Design Thinking methodology (Empathize → Define → Ideate → Prototype → Test) and the UK Design Council's Double Diamond (Discover → Define → Develop → Deliver) are the gold-standard industry frameworks for the Brainstorm phase. These frameworks explicitly mandate: (1) Divergent thinking before convergent thinking — generating many ideas before narrowing, (2) Separate "Define" phase that synthesizes research before ideation begins, (3) Low-fidelity prototyping and testing before committing to a spec, and (4) Iterative cycles through the diamond rather than a linear progression. The current Phase 1 skills are convergent-only: idea_to_spec immediately narrows to one spec, user_story_standards immediately formalizes into a story. There is no "generate 10 alternative approaches to this problem" step, no "crazy 8s" ideation, no design sprint methodology, and no low-fidelity paper prototype before Phase 2 design work begins.
### Proposed Resolution: New skill `ideation_workshop` in Phase 1. Trigger: "brainstorm solutions", "ideation session", "design sprint". Scope: Facilitates divergent ideation (How Might We questions, Crazy 8s, analogous inspiration from different industries), convergence via dot voting and effort/impact matrix, and selection of top 2-3 directions for prototyping before committing to a full spec. Integrates with Design Sprint 2.0 methodology (Jake Knapp / GV).
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without structured ideation, the first idea that surfaces becomes the product direction. Phase 2 designs solutions that were never validated against alternatives. Phase 3 builds the obvious solution rather than the best solution.
================================================================

## Finding: INDUSTRY DEVIATION — No Lean Canvas / Lean Startup Methodology

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: The Lean Startup methodology (Eric Ries) and Lean Canvas (Ash Maurya) are industry-standard frameworks specifically for the Brainstorm phase of new products. Lean Canvas covers: Problem (top 3 problems), Solution (top 3 features), Unique Value Proposition, Unfair Advantage, Customer Segments, Key Metrics, Channels, Cost Structure, and Revenue Streams — all on one page. The Build-Measure-Learn loop is the industry-standard for validating ideas before building. Neither lean canvas nor the build-measure-learn loop appears anywhere in Phase 1. The closest equivalent is idea_to_spec, but it is not equivalent: it jumps directly to implementation spec without the validation cycle. The framework's approach skips from "brain dump" directly to implementation.
### Proposed Resolution: Add `lean_canvas` as a Phase 1 skill. Trigger: "lean canvas", "one-page business model", "validate before building". Scope: Guides completion of a Lean Canvas for the product/feature, identifies which box has the highest uncertainty (the riskiest assumption), and designs a Minimum Viable Product (MVP) experiment to validate it. Canvas output feeds directly into assumption_testing skill (Loop 1) and business_model_validation skill (Loop 1).
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without a Lean Canvas, products proceed to Phase 2 without a one-page articulation of the business model. Phase 5 GTM strategy cannot reference a business model that was never documented.
================================================================

## Finding: INDUSTRY DEVIATION — No Jobs-to-be-Done (JTBD) Framework at Phase Level

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: user_story_standards includes JTBD format as a story writing option ("When [situation], I want to [motivation], so I can [expected outcome]"). But JTBD as a product strategy framework (Clayton Christensen / Bob Moesta) operates at a level above user stories: it identifies the "progress" customers are trying to make in their lives, the functional/emotional/social jobs they are hiring a product to do, and the forces of progress vs. forces of inertia. No Phase 1 skill applies full JTBD theory: no "Forces Diagram" analysis, no "demand-side selling" research protocol, no "switch interviews" (understanding what triggered a customer to switch from their current solution to a new one), and no job mapping to identify under-served job segments.
### Proposed Resolution: Extend user_research to include a JTBD research protocol variant with: Switch interview guide (four forces: push of current situation, pull of new solution, anxiety about new, attachment to old), Job map template (8-step job map: define → locate → prepare → confirm → execute → monitor → modify → conclude), and job sizing worksheet (which jobs are most under-served and highest-value). This data directly feeds prioritization_frameworks.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without JTBD, product teams optimize features rather than hiring occasions. Phase 3 builds technically correct features that nobody buys because the switching triggers are not understood.
================================================================

## Finding: INDUSTRY DEVIATION — No OWASP Threat Modeling at Spec Stage

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: HIGH
### Evidence: OWASP mandates that threat modeling occurs early in the SDLC — ideally during requirements/design, not during security review. The OWASP STRIDE framework (Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information Disclosure, Denial of Service, Elevation of Privilege) should be applied to every feature spec before design begins. idea_to_spec has a SECURITY section with three fields (auth required, who, validation) but no STRIDE analysis, no data flow diagram for threat surface identification, no privacy impact assessment (PIA) for features handling personal data, and no security requirements specification that feeds Phase 4 (Secure). Phase 4 performs security audits on completed code — but OWASP's secure SDLC mandates that security requirements are captured in Phase 1, not discovered in Phase 4.
### Proposed Resolution: Add a "Security by Design" section to idea_to_spec that includes: (1) Data classification (what data does this feature handle? PII? Financial? Health?), (2) STRIDE threat enumeration (which of the 6 STRIDE threats apply to this feature?), (3) Privacy Impact Assessment trigger (if PII is handled: "Run PIA before spec is finalized"), (4) Security requirements (specific, testable security requirements that Phase 4 will verify), and (5) Compliance flag (does this feature trigger GDPR Article 25 Privacy by Design requirements?). This aligns with OWASP SAMM (Software Assurance Maturity Model) practice SR1.1.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 4 (Secure) currently discovers security requirements. With OWASP-aligned Phase 1, security requirements arrive in Phase 4 already specified, and Phase 4 becomes verification rather than discovery. This dramatically reduces Phase 4 cycle time and eliminates security-driven rework in Phase 3.
================================================================

## Finding: INDUSTRY DEVIATION — No Accessibility (WCAG / Section 508) Requirement Capture

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: No Phase 1 skill mentions accessibility. WCAG 2.1 (Web Content Accessibility Guidelines) is the international standard and a legal requirement under ADA, Section 508 (US federal), EN 301 549 (EU). The European Accessibility Act (EAA) became enforceable in June 2025, meaning European products launched without accessibility compliance face legal liability. idea_to_spec has no accessibility field. user_story_standards has no accessibility story pattern. user_research has no guidance on including users with disabilities in research panels. A product that completes Phase 1 under this framework may have zero accessibility requirements documented — meaning accessibility will be retrofitted (expensively) or shipped non-compliant.
### Proposed Resolution: Add to idea_to_spec REQUIREMENTS section: "Accessibility: WCAG 2.1 Level A / AA / AAA (default: AA)" and "Target Assistive Technologies: Screen readers? Keyboard-only navigation? High contrast?". Add to user_story_standards a non-functional accessibility story template: "As a user with [disability], I need [feature] to [work in a specific way] so that I can [accomplish goal]." Add to user_research guidance to include at least 1 participant with a relevant disability in each usability test round.
### Cross-Phase Impact: Phase 3 (Build) developers build inaccessible UIs. Phase 4 discovers compliance violations after code is written. Retrofitting accessibility to a completed product is typically 3-5x more expensive than building it in from the start.
================================================================

## Finding: INDUSTRY DEVIATION — No Product-Market Fit (PMF) Framework

### Gap Type: INDUSTRY_DEVIATION
### Severity: MEDIUM
### Evidence: Sean Ellis's Product-Market Fit survey ("How would you feel if you could no longer use this product?" with 40% threshold for "Very disappointed"), the Superhuman PMF methodology, and the Y Combinator "Do people want this?" framework are industry-standard gates for Phase 1. No Phase 1 skill applies any PMF framework. product_metrics covers NPS (Net Promoter Score) but NPS is a satisfaction metric, not a PMF metric. The distinction matters: high NPS ≠ PMF. Retention curves (do they come back?), engagement depth (do they use core features?), and disappointment scores are the PMF-validating signals. Currently, Phase 1 produces metrics plans but no PMF validation methodology.
### Proposed Resolution: Add a "PMF Signal Definition" section to product_metrics covering: (1) Sean Ellis survey setup and 40% threshold interpretation, (2) Retention curve analysis for early users (Day 1, Day 7, Day 30 retention targets that indicate PMF trajectory), (3) Engagement depth signals (which actions indicate a user has found value?), and (4) PMF readiness gate (what signals tell you PMF is achieved and Phase 5 (Ship) / scaling is appropriate?).
### Cross-Phase Impact: Without a PMF framework, products scale (Phase 5 Ship) before PMF is achieved. This is the primary cause of startup failure — premature scaling of an unvalidated product consumes all resources before product-market fit is found.
================================================================

